Paso Robles has lots of fun winemaking, and is an interesting terroir with soils that encourage good acidity. Non Bordeaux varietals seem to take on great character, so this type of messed up red blend is really something that makes me give this often flabby and overdone area some attention. This producer is exciting, doing fun things, recognizing the potential of this area, and loves sustainability. All these grapes are pretty massive and dark, erring peppery with black fruits.

I just deleted a few sentences on the craft of the blend, but uh, basically, it’s mostly black fruit flavors, some spices, and hints of chocolate and anise add complexity if you need it. Dense stuff but somehow it remains elegant and not overdone and would be a wonderful wine for a big dish, or alone as a way to drown your existential woes.

Natural: minimal added sulphur, organic, natural fermentation, etc. Moulin-A-Vent is a fun Cru Beaujolais, of middling latitude, "the most tannic, sturdy, long lasting" area typically due to shitty soils that reduce yields which is great for making good wine grapes!

Terroir driven, 114 year old vines, great concentration of fruit flavors with a wonderful minerality underlying everything. Not super tannic of course, it's still Gamay, but this thing is a serious wine you could happily get a few more years out of... not that you couldn't enjoy it fresh either.

Organic / bio / natural, with minimal sulphur at bottling.

This is from Dom de L’Ecu, which is another favorite producer from the Loire valley, doing old school wines that are very “natural”, super terroir driven options.

Mostly dark fruits with some forest floor, and touches of meaty spices. Lift of mint and smoke on the finish. Balanced, but dark and lush, pair with meats!

Item Name: Lucio Wax canvas Apron w/ Liner

Description:
Lunaria is brought in by a local importer: always organic, vegan friendly, more naturally made.

Super food friendly, and this comes in a 3L BIB format. Totally badass.

Full of black cherry, some lighter plum, touches of dried herbs and chocolates. Soft, with tannin, and fresh acidity. Incredible with a lot of foods.

Item Name: Lunaria Ramoro Pinot Grigio Terre di Chieti 2018
Description: The brand is locally owned, and puts a big emphasis on organics and lower intervention production all the way around, showcasing many wonderful wines from Italy in fun packaging. This looks and drinks like a rose, but is made all from pinot grigio which we typically see as a white wine. Fresh strawberries, delicate floral aromatics, light body, crushable but with delicacy. Awesome stuff in the whole range!

Item Name: Lustau Brandy de Jerez Sherry Cask
Luxardo Sour Cherry Gin & Tonic 4 Pack

Description:
Cool very "New World" production. Notice there's no vintage statement, the grapes change lot to lot, etc.

It's a zin based blend with a bunch of other sh*t in there. Lower intervention etc... nerdy and fun.

This is a crowd pleasing more naturally presented wine. Great balance, mix of lighter and darker fruits with a little spice. Great with food or on its own. Easy!

Item Name: Mars Maltage Cosmo Wine Cask Finish 2020 750ml

Description: A famous winemaker in the Napa Valley, this husband and wife duo makes wines that are respected by all. They do all kinds of fun blends and work with less popular varietals, but are most known for the great quality of their chardonnays and cabernets. Beautiful dark fruits, hints of minerality and leather that won't take away from the good weight, long finish, and just easy lower-than-typical ABV drinking. Drink it now, or sit on it for a while!

Argentina Malbec can provide some real gems and values; this grape originally coming from Bordeaux offers a spicy, jammy, not too acidic experience with a blend of brighter and darker fruits and a toasted vanilla finish. A great red to drink alone or throw with some burgers.

Description: Owen Roe offers many great value Washington wines, more reserved than their Cali counterparts but just as fun. This is a clean unoaked chardonnay, with flavors of lemon, pear, and starfruit. I'd pair this with lemon chicken, or a summer salad.

Item Name: Modern Mixology Rona Diamond Cut Beaker

Description: This stuff slaps, as the kids are wont to say. Very natural producer; classic / champagne method, made entirely from Corvina (a red grape). Even the dosage is leftover must from Amarone production instead of just throwing in sugar for dosage and second fermentation. One of the nerdiest things we have, and certainly amongst the tastiest. Give it a go, you'll love it!

Barbera is a great thing to have around for any occasion. Darker fruits, medium body, nice acidity, great with food or alone. Uncomplicated. You can even give it a light chill which is great for Texans. One of the more friendly styles from Italy, if you want a lighter red to try out with a meal this will be sure to make you smile.

Item Name: Murray Hill Club Special Release Bourbon 750ml

Description: This is a traditional method sparkling wine from Spain. It smells like apples or melons, tart citrus, with a touch of toasty brine. Great for cocktails, as an apertif, or with a range of foods! One of the great values.

Description:
Paul Cluver is organic farming, sustainable, with minimal intervention in an overall fun style across their range. Nice!

This ripe and easy Sauvignon Blanc is aromatic, with a great full texture supporting big fruit flavors. Pair this with fish, pork, or enjoy it totally alone!

Honeyed citrus notes, some minerals for depth, a slightly sharp texture to the bubbles, pleasing acidity, some green apple complexity on the mid palate. Just old school classic champagne. They're a "big house" doing a lot of great things.

Honeyed citrus notes, some minerals for depth, a slightly sharp texture to the bubbles, pleasing acidity, some green apple complexity on the mid palate. Just old school classic champagne. They're a "big house" doing a lot of great things.

Peter Franus seems to just make solid new world wines. I think they’re working with some vineyards that are organic or bio, but not all. They’re never over extracted or overripe, they understand terroir yet the final product is just friendly as hell.

This 14.8ABV Zin is responsible, cherries and vanilla galore with vibrancy. An earlier harvest than most keeps things in balance. Still a big wine though, and would kill with barbecue, hamburgers, grilled things, etc. Big fun summer red!

Item Name: Pinhook Humor Straight Rye Cask Strength 750ml

Description: Fully organic / natural. Serbian natural pinot noir, yea, that's not normal. Hot country with a long wine making tradition, this gets made using techniques to control over ripening but it still gets a pretty nice full and dark and lush flavor set for a pinot. More power than many offerings, with loads of character. Throw this with a lot of foods, drink it alone, whatever! It's really dang unique!!

Item Name: PM Spirits Tequila Blanco Still Strength 750ml

Description: Converted to more organic farming practices, the 2/3 Roussanne and 1/3 Gruener Veltliner blend isn't set in stone year to year but this vintage I think is the most balanced yet. Of course you get pretty low intervention winemaking. More neutral, with green apple, some melon, a decent body, and balanced acidity. Great alone, or pretty food friendly due to the decent body for what it is.

Poggio Anima is a great producer that apparently is super into Eastern philosophy that do lots of cool single vineyard releases. Their stuff is always friendly and very value driven, plus most Italian wines lean ‘natural’.

Fun starter: this bottling is named after the angel of death (Samael). Montepulciano usually has good color, ABV, and dark fruit like plums, earth, sometimes even a little “smokey” seeming. A touch of oak can bring out a little chocolate too. As far as Italian varietals go, this is lower acid, so still good acid (lol), and mild but present tannins.

This is a friendly and value driven Italian wine that’s fruity like plums but with some nice earthiness too! As food friendly as it gets!

Description: A blend that's subject to change each vintage, Southold presents this as their intro to their style of Texas red wine. Geeky fresh and fun and easy with almost sour candied watermelon and citrus flavors, and a finish that gives just a breath of funk. Can be served with a light chill. Perfect Texas summer red wine!

Item Name: Southold Farm Shot Across the Bow 2017 750ml

Description: Tradtional / champagne method, an unconventional blend of grapes that yields intriguing color, a yeasty and serious nose, with earth and cardamom and less fruit than most Southolds. A pleasant texture and weight.
This Sangiovese red is perhaps my favorite of the more standard offerings - bright, crushable, light, refreshing, friendly, and fun. Naturally made, fairly priced, we're a fan!

Description: From a nerdy and more naturally minded producer, this wine is from a prone-to-mutation grape mostly seen in cooler areas of Europe. The nose is aromatic, full of white peaches and pears, lemon, and some lanolin. The palate follows with slightly candied floral notes, medium body, and lime-like brightness. Balanced, refreshing without being a citrus bomb, and decent depth. A great summer white!

Item Name: The Craft of the Cocktail Revised Edition

Description: Bedrock Wine Co. is a really cool group behind this project. This is a mostly Zinfandel based blend and if you notice there's no vintage on it, they blend what they have as needed which honestly gives you a lot of options and room to just do what needs to be done! This is a fun juicy New World blend, a lot of Zinfandel in here. It's got gorgeous ripe fruit, a full smooth body, with a refreshing finish that'll leave you coming back for more. Have fun with this one!

Item Name: Through The Grapevine Vallein Tercinier 1988 Cognac

Description:
Greek wines seem to be catching on more and more, and this is gonna be a characterful wine that people will remember. A lot of cool orange wines and other natural wines come from Greece too, so keep an eye out!

"Here's a rustic charmer from Greece, with a light body but a mixture of complex dark fruits all in a slightly smoky package with tinges of herbaceousness. Have fun pairing this with meats and cheeses!"

Washinton syrah is an undersung hero as-is, but oh gosh, is this just a shocking stunner of a value. Syrah brings a fuller body and nice cherry and strawberry, but the slight CO2 influence makes it obnoxiously refreshing. We didn't want to like it as much as we did but don't miss out on this, and don't be scared of cans!

This dry bianco is a fun blend of grapes (Favorita, Arneis, Moscato) with a little bit of CO2 left in the bottle to make for the ultimate porch-pounding refreshing experience. Italian producer Tintero offers so many wonderful, crushable offerings showing the incredible value that Italy can offer. Sustainable, like their others - try 'em all!

Why do you monsters not like Moscato? Because you’re wrong, and have probably never had a good one. A lot of them are harvested from not great grapes so they don’t get real ripeness, then sugar is added to make sure they’re sweet and to get more yield, and never balanced against proper acid from doing things right. Tintero is a pretty damn legit producer making real Moscato in the way that got Asti well recognized for these clean refreshing wines.

It smells like flowers, all kinds of wonderful flowers from honeysuckle to orange blossom, with gentle ripe pear. On the palate, there’s a wonderful gentle bubbly texture, and the sweetness is in balance with good acidity. All y’all complainin’ ‘bout sugar, I see y’all drinking cocktails etc. This is like an elderflower already bottled spritz cocktail thing at 3 bucks a glass. Great dessert, digestif, aperitif, whatever. Don’t be scared.

Italian producer Tintero offers so many wonderful, crushable offerings showing the incredible value that Italy can offer. This rose is a fun blend of grapes with a little bit of CO2 left in the bottle to make for the ultimate porch-pounding refreshing experience. A best seller, and a wonderful producer. Try all their offerings!

Pears, some lemon curd, toast, nutmeg, vanilla, floral. Remains overall balanced, and the oaken influences are pleasant and of quality. This isn’t some manipulated and oak chipped monstrosity - this is a legit and well awarded producer of new world chardonnay.

Item Name: Topo Chico Hard Seltzer Variety 12 Pack

Description: Refreshing and dry. Bright fruits, flowers, a frothy texture. Just great value bubbly that’s at home in any glass or cocktail. Keep one around for French 75s, mimosa Sunday, or a cheery lil’ aperitif. For the money, this is a great choice.
Soft, ripe light berries, floral and offering great value, this Pinot Noir is a great wine to keep around for the table or anytime you need a gentle pick-me-up. Pair with a wide range of dishes!

Description: History in a bottle. Naturally made orange wine in a historic style that dominated most of history in Italy. 2011 is the current vintage (lots of resting), and its had time to develop some really interesting character and soften up. Quite unfiltered, with a funky yeasty note that opens into apricot, teas, spices, and tree fruits. Not super heavy bodied as this is from pinot grigio, but you’ll certainly sense the structure.

This wine tastes overall simple like dark juicy plums, a little blueberry, with some vanilla and chocolate warmth from oak. Full and lush without being flabby, a great "any occasion" wine. Organic grapes, cute label, lots to love. Not just a pretty bottle, though that never hurts!

Dry Austrian riesling, how nifty! Riesling I think most people associate with off-dry wines; this is bone dry. A profound wine that I'm super stoked to see us carrying. A sustainable/organic producer!

It's got a lovely floral and honeyed ripe white fruit aroma, with steel-like minerality and a little more body than German offerings. Great with delicate foods!

Description:
South African pinotage is a whole thing with some history that's fun to read about, it's a hybrid grape you basically only see in South Africa. It didn't have a great reputation for some time, but now people are giving it more attention and making much better wines. This is an example thereof from a winery that puts focus on sustainability, good farming practices, and natural wine making processes.

This was made with "whole cluster fermentation", giving it a really fresh and fruity character that's very approachable and drinkable. Lighter overall, you could even put a light chill on it if you want to.
